Alpes, France","Albon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Albon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","Domène, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Domène, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Countess","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire, of Norman origin): from Middle English <i>contas(e)</i>, Old French <i>contesse</i> ‘countess’, applied as a nickname for a proud, haughty woman or for a foppish man, or as an occupational name for a servant of a countess."],"variants":[{"name":"Countiss","meanings":["English: variant of   Countess  ."]}]},{"name":"Of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Albon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Alban  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alban","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Alfonso, Alvaro, Jaime, Luis, Prudencio, Alberto, Andres, Guillermo.","English; Spanish (<b>Albán</b>): from the personal name <i>Alban</i>, Spanish <i>Albán</i>, from Latin <i>Albanus</i>, originally a habitational name for someone from any of the many places in Italy and elsewhere called Alba.","Galician (<b>Albán</b>): habitational name from any of the places called Albán in Galicia, Spain."]}]},{"name":"Petronille","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old female name; an Italian diminutive formed from Pietro, i.e. Peter."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Petronille Or Gothelina Countess Of Albon was born about 1050, in Albon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France, her father, Artaud Seigneur d'Annonay, was 52 and her mother, Petronel, was 41. She married Guigue II Count Of Albon on 27 April 1050. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She was buried in Domène, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France."},"et":{"ABT 1027–":"umbes 1050–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1025–1079":"1025–1079","1060–1117":"1060–1